    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-01-09T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-01-09T10:00:00-05:00" n="889"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d889">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 EW/l–945: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-01-09T18:00:00+03:00"
                            >January 9, 1945—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 9:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>87. The Czech Ambassador has given me a copy of a memorandum which he has
                    submitted to the Narkomindel<note n="4a" xml:id="d889fn4a">Soviet People’s
                        Commissariat for Foreign Affairs (Narodnyi Komissariat I nostrannykh
                        Del).</note> containing certain Czech desiderata in relation to the
                    Hungarian and German armistice terms. The memorandum suggests that the following
                    points be included in the Hungarian armistice: <list>
                        <label>(1)</label>
                        <item>A proposal that certain enactments, such as the Vienna Awards, which
                            affect Czech territory be recognized as null and void.</item>
                        <label>(2)</label>
                        <item>That it be stipulated that a state of war between Czechoslovakia and
                            Hungary existed as of October 7, 1938.</item>
                        <label>(3)</label>
                        <item>A proposal that Hungary take on certain obligations with respect to
                            Magyars who possessed Czech citizenship but who will be transferred to
                            Hungary.</item>
                        <label>(4)</label>
                        <item>A proposal that Czechoslovakia participate in the occupation of
                            Hungary if states other than Great Britain and the United States, <pb
                                facs="0980" n="968" xml:id="pg_968"/> the Soviet Union and France
                            participate in the occupation of that country.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>I understand from the British Embassy that the Czech proposals were presented in
                    full to the Department early in December. Since it is likely that these
                    proposals will be raised when we present the Hungarian draft to the Czech and
                    Yugoslav Ambassadors here (Department’s 2764, December 1, 4 p.m. and penultimate
                    paragraph of Embassy’s 5034, December 27, 9 p.m.), I would appreciate
                    Department’s views thereon.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
